asciiplanets(1)              User Commands             asciiplanets(1)



NAME
       asciiplanets - ASCII solar system observer

SYNOPSIS
       asciiplanets   [--crosshair|-c]   [--font-aspect   FONT_ASPECT]
       [--help|-h] [--no-colors] [--no-trailing-newline|-T]  [--offset
       OFFSET] [--outer] [--radius RADIUS] [--size SIZE]

DESCRIPTION
       Show  planets in our solar system using simple ASCII characters
       and some ANSI espace codes (if you chose to).

OPTIONS
       --crosshair, -c
              Draw a crosshair aiming at the sun. Equinoxes occur when
              the  earth  passes  the horizontal line, solstices occur
              when the earth passes  the  vertical  line.  The  “left”
              equinox happens around March.

       --font-aspect FONT_ASPECT
              Set font aspect ratio (width / height). Defaults to 0.5.

       -h, --help
              Show a brief help summary.

       --no-colors
              Disable colors.

       --no-trailing-newline
              Do not print a newline after the last row.

       --offset OFFSET
              Time offset in days.

       --outer
              Show  outer  solar  system.  By default, the inner solar
              system is shown.

       --radius RADIUS
              Maximum radius to show, in astronomical units.  This  is
              an alternative to --outer.

       --size SIZE
              Terminal size, e.g. 80x24. If set to auto (the default),
              let asciiplanets find out the current size.

DEPENDENCIES
       ·   Python 3

       ·   pyephem

LICENSE
       asciiplanets is released as “PIZZA-WARE”. See the  accompanying
       LICENSE file.

HISTORY
       asciiplanets  was  originally  written  by  Peter  Hofmann. The
       project was started in February 2015.



